I think there are 2 problems:
1. Uploading copies of the same model. This artificially increases the score of a model. Also, copies receive rewards, although I don't believe this is a significant problem.
2. Good models become stale. This is caused by 1. (Artificially boosted models are in the top 5 instead of a good model) and randomness in sampled examples.

Some syncing could address 2., e.g. sample one model from the consensus every step.

One possible solution for 1.
Calculate winrates, drop the worst model, and repeat until there are only 5 models left.
E.g.
There are models 1 2 3 4 5, and someone uploads 3 copies of model 6. Right now one of the models 6 still scores well because it has a 100% win rate vs the other two.

I think one of the complicating factors is that the loss value of a model is highly dependent on the samples that are evaluated (an emperical observation). So validators will often not agree on the best model, as they all see the models through a different lens. This, combined with upload of duplicates and the queue length of 5 (as far as I can see in the source code), turns it into a game that is not (only) about generating the objectively best model anymore, for miners at least. One easy fix could be to increase the number of samples evaluated, and/or by taking samples from more than two wandb runs, e.g. by taking 50-100 random samples per wandb run. There is an explanation for the recent changes in LB dynamics and for the vtrust issues: wandb often returns old data. Some runs are somehow stalled and return the same "last history step" for hours and sometimes days. E.g. look at run id mr8u9a0v, wandb url https://wandb.ai/cortex-t/multi-modality/runs/mr8u9a0v, which is at "last history step" 2694 for about 267 hours (yes, 11 days) now. That means that if you would (over)train a model on recent wandb data with an insane learning rate, you can train your model to the point where the loss on, say, "Explore the concept of impedance in AC circuits and its significance in regulating current flow" (the first question of step 2694) is in the order of 0.01. Any normally trained model (i.e. a model intended to be a fine-tuned LLM suitable for answering a broad set of new questions) will lose to an overtrained model, as a typical loss of a truly new question is in the order of 0.5 or higher.

So, you might wonder, how does this explain LB dynamics and vtrust issues? To understand this, you need to understand how validation works in subnet 6. A validator fetches "recent" validation data from wandb, and receives a list of "runs". This list is shuffled and then processed one by one. Of each run, the "last history step" is taken (wandb data is stored in "steps," which may be seen as rows in a table). Each run may supply up to 256 prompt+response pairs in such a step, but typically yields 200 valid P+R pairs. At most 400 pairs are collected, so the collected validation data is typically sourced from two runs. Typically there are 14-21 runs active. Suppose now, that 5 runs are "stalled" in the way described above, and return the same data for at least a few hours. A model that is overtrained on "recent data" will know everything about these 5 "stalled" runs and nothing about the other runs, as the data of these other runs is, at time of validation, not in the "last history step" but in an older step.

Now validation occurs. Each validator effectively selects two runs to validate the top-5 ("consensus") models, plus new models. Suppose there is a set of 5 good models in the consensus pool, and a new model is posted that is heavily overtrained on recent data. Suppose the two selected runs are from the 5 "stalled" runs: the new, overtrained, model will win with a landslide; win rate 100%. Suppose the two runs are *not* from the "stalled" set of runs: the new, overtrained, model will lose hard; win rate 0%. The weight given by this validator to the particular new model will either be high or low, depending on chance alone. As each validator takes its own random set, they will often not agree with one another. This explains the vtrust issues.

So how about the leaderboard? Suppose that there are no "stalled" runs: no overtraining will ever get you near a good score. The good models in the consensus pool will keep getting a (fair) score, and their relative position on the leaderboard will not change much. New models will have to be better, truly better, on answering questions, to get a decent score. Now suppose that 50% of runs stall - now everything starts to move, as newcomers will sometimes gain high scores and knock the good models off the leaderboard. Now imagine people adjusting their behavior to these effects, and the number of stalled runs fluctuating on a daily basis...
How to fix this? It is quite simple, really. Wandb returns, with the Prompt+Response data of the step, a timestamp. The validator could use this timestamp to ignore data older than, say, 10 minutes.

As soon as this is implemented, I predict that the vtrust and LB will become much more stable. Subnet 6 will become a bit more boring, because it will become slow, in the sense that we will not be seeing new models being pushed every hour. But it will be about training a good model, not about overtraining models. I also suspect that the whole model copying and double uploading will be less interesting; at the current state of affairs, you can finetune such strategies and experiment daily, probably generating a decent amount of TAO. By making it about training a good model, and slowing down the pace, the opportunities and incentives for such metagaming will probably lessen.
